1092,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-25 01:36:42+00:00,112024290,caronc/apprise,850374,caronc,,,325908700,391915171,"I'm using OpenELEC myself (which is a bit dated), but I'm quite certain it's using Kodi 17. I can say without a doubt thought that the kodi:// (v6 API) works great. I don't think i ever got the images/icons the work though; it always just put the icon provided by Kodi.
If you add **-vvv** you'll get enough verbosity that you can see the payload being sent to your (Kodi) server.

Rolling back to v2 (of the API) is still an option without any software changes; you can achieve this by just using **xbmc://** instead of **kodi://** (in apprise) if you want.

I've always applauded Kodi's ability to maintain backwards compatibility with all of it's APIs.  It would have made sense if it was _v2_ (of the API) that didn't work and _v6_ did, but since it's the other way around it's almost seems like there might be a bug in the build of Kodi you're using.

All that said, from my end: I don't think there would be much effort involved in creating a flag such as **?version=X** or something that you could add to the (apprise) URL if you think the protocol should be different then the default ([v6](https://kodi.wiki/view/JSON-RPC_API/v6)).  It would involve writing at least 6 new functions though (one for API v1, 3,4,5,7 & 8).  So i don' t know if there is value here. Might be overkill though.

Your thoughts?",{},OWNER,User,False
1095,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-13 20:26:45+00:00,84624509,cdgriffith/Box,3275435,cdgriffith,,,296844694,365393291,"I will have to think about this more / get more feedback, but right now it sounds like it's acting like Python expects. (That you can have integers, really anything hashable, as keys of the dict. But attributes have to be strictly strings) 

```python
>>> class A:
...     pass
...
>>> a = A()
>>> b = dict()
>>> b[1] = 1
>>> setattr(a, 1, 1)
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
TypeError: attribute name must be string, not 'int'
```

Python will raise unavoidable syntax errors if someones tries to access or set an integer via dot notation, so that can't be circumvented (i.e. `a.1 = 1` would raise SyntaxError). So someone would have to be using `getattr`, `setattr` or manually calling the magic functions to see this error, which is already past the point of this module trying to be handy by allowing access dot attribute access to non-string keys. 




",{},OWNER,User,False
