1724,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-23 16:25:30+00:00,8307391,mahmoud/boltons,2320029,induane,,,189792456,262562827,"Also @kurtbrose the hash implementation might be trouble on excessively large numbers of dictionary keys but it'll only ever be calculated once per object instance so I'd suspect it might not be the worst thing ever. It's not always going to be calculated either.

One of the reasons to implement hash is so that an object can be used in a hashmap. If the frozendict (FrozenDict?) is hashable using an underlying hash then it is possible that both a frozendict and an identical object (tuple, whatever is used behind the scenes) could end up with an identical hash value which in turn could cause key collisions. That's probably such an obscure scenario that it's not a big deal, but possibly worth considering as well.


",{},,User,False
