2309,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-02 09:35:15+00:00,15883067,xflr6/fileconfig,6342379,xflr6,,,83731062,107888460,"Sure, `fileconfig` uses `ConfigParser` from the stdlib under the hood (though you can override that). The latter provides config file parsing with a basic `get(section, option)` API, while `fileconfig` builds upon that to providing an API for a more specialized use case: config file sections as singleton instances of a user-defined class, aliasing, inheritance, and overlay of build-in and user-provided config.

Say, you write an app for running/automating specific tasks. Each task is defined by a config file section. Some tasks are build-in, and users can add their own by putting them in their config file. For you as an app writer this will be only a few lines of a `fileconfig.Stacked` subclass definition containing your buissness logic and a config file residing inside your package directory. Loading user config files boils down to `YourClass.add(<filename>)`. All the logic to make that possible (e.g. resolving paths relative to currently executed file) is done in the background by the `fileconfig` package.

I extracted this functionality from an earlier draft of the `features` package as it looked to me like a logical chunk of one separatable functionality that might be reusable later/by others. Even if there would never be a case for reusing, it seems easier to test and refine a nicely moduarlized piece of software than a bigger monolitic block.",{},,User,False
