4718,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-07 17:28:02+00:00,30582779,warner/magic-wormhole,27146,warner,,,158204858,292600134,"This got rewritten in #42, but we still need some way for a WelcomeError to interrupt `input_code`. It's not easy, because we've got a separate thread, sitting in a blocking call to `input()`. What we really need is a way to tell readline to give up from the outside. I'm pretty sure the low-level python glue has some sort of periodic timer; if it was checking a flag or something, maybe we could write to that flag and tell it to bail.
",{},,User,False
4730,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-10 22:19:33+00:00,30582779,warner/magic-wormhole,27146,warner,,,198278707,300629315,"Meejah and I were brainstorming about this, and we figured out an initial client change that could smooth the way forward if/when we need to turn something on in the future:

* make the client look for a new Welcome message field, maybe named `permission-token-url`
* if present, the client should display a message to the user, basically ""please point a web browser at this URL, do what it tells you, then paste back in the token that it shows you""
  * after a few seconds, maybe have the client can pop open a browser window to the URL
  * but if the client is running in `--tor` mode, maybe don't: we don't want to make it easy for the server to force the client to reveal anything identifying, if the user has a better/safer way to get the token
* the client should have a box or an input field for the token, which must be ASCII and easy to cut/paste
* when the client gets the token from the user, it should send it in a new message to the server, maybe `{type=""submit-permission"", token=TOKEN}`, then continue with the protocol

The idea is that we don't know what sorts of PoW or CAPTCHA we might need in the future, but there's a decent chance that it will be implementable by a web browser. So if we make the client capable of delegating this work (through the user) to a browser today, then we can wait until we actually need it before we go and build something.

This doesn't limit us to a CAPTCHA.. anything that serves a rate-limiting or auditing purpose would do. ""Log in with github"". Even just demonstrating control over an IP address would let the server do some anti-abuse classification (e.g. if we see a lot of nameplate allocation or failed guesses coming from the same IP address, treat it as malicious and block or rate-limit it).

GUI clients that can open up web views (e.g. the Tahoe setup tool named https://github.com/gridsync that @crwood is building, which I think is a QT app) could open the requested URL directly in the app, rather than using an external web browser. If the app-webview API allows for manipulation of the page environment, we could create a return pathway for the token that wouldn't require the user to copy/paste anything (we did something like this in Persona a few years ago, basically the web page calls `window.MagicWormhole.deliver_token(TOKEN)` if that object exists).

Decisions to make:

* name of the Welcome message field
* name of the token-return message
* ordering of the messages
  * something that plays well with current clients (backwards-compatible, graceful upgrade)
  * current servers send WELCOME right away. current clients send BIND and ALLOCATE or CLAIM right away
  * option 1: servers buffer the BIND/ALLOCATE/CLAIM if they want a token, send demand for token in WELCOME, wait for new SUBMIT-PERMISSION message, then allow buffered messages to be delivered
  * option 2: servers reject BIND without a token, by sending WELCOME with an error=. Sounds unworkable, would need to behave sort of like HTTP ""Authorization"" header where the first request is rejected but includes instructions for how to make a successful second request. We need some way to carry state from the challenge to the response.
  * option 3: don't buffer BIND/ALLOCATE/CLAIM (discard them instead), use WELCOME to indicate need for a token, somehow tell the client that it must re-send BIND (with token=) and ALLOCATE/CLAIM. Maybe do this by resetting the client state machines back to the ""not connected"" state, then faking a connection event
",{},,User,False
