6897,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-14 23:29:28+00:00,27609645,web2py/pydal,10407290,stephenrauch,33118,web2py,94530396,121427633,"@ilvalle 

Thanks for the comment. 

I am aware the a distinct() call that does not resolve to unique results will give differing results in different situations or backends. I am also aware that groupby is generally better to use. In fact distinct uses the '$group' pipeline stage on Mongo. But that is not my question. My question is: does it even work? Because on both of the SQL backends I have available (MSSQL and SQLite) it does not work. Any combination of your example I try on sqlite bombs with the error:

```
OperationalError: near ""."": syntax error
```

In addition, You gave two examples:

> For example on postgres the following works:

```
db().select(db.tt.aa, db.tt.bb, distinct=db.tt.aa)
```

> while this is not allowed:

```
db().select(db.tt.aa, db.tt.bb, distinct=db.tt.aa)
```

These two examples appear to me to be identical. So I am confused.

To date I have tried to validate all of the functionality I have added to the mongo driver with test cases. I have also tried to insure that all of the test cases also work on sqlite and mssql. But in this case I failed to get anything other than distinct=True to work on either driver.

I am far from an expert on SQL, and so have been relying on the test suite and the book as the defacto specification for my mongo driver work.

At this point I have already submitted the mongo code and tests.  I am trying to back port all of my added tests which are appropriate to SQL to the sql.py test file, and this test doesn't work.  During the back port I will simply ignore the test for distinct is something other than True.

Thanks.",{},,User,False
