7303,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-30 15:51:23+00:00,6930489,facebook/watchman,117777,wez,69631,facebook,326760585,393214329,"We used to do this and removed it; here are some randomly ordered bullet points with context:

*  It is too expensive to spin up the watch on-demand on large repos
* This makes it difficult to manage expectations; should the query timeout after a couple of seconds, or minutes?
* There's no way in the protocol to advise the client that we're now doing something unexpected, so no good way to show progress UI

Forcing the client to explicitly watch-project first ends up being nicer for the end-user at the expense of being a little bit more awkward for the integrator:

* The watch-project call can have an appropriate (longer!) timeout configured around it, and a progress UI can explicit indicate that it is waiting for the project to be made available to watchman
* The query call can have a more reasonable and short timeout configured
* It's clearer to everyone what is going on
",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
