7695,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-12 21:44:37+00:00,1257514,quantmind/pulsar,144320,lsbardel,144099,quantmind,116440129,156245602,"Your ``push`` method returns a coroutine (generator) and therefore it does not comply with pulsar [asynchronous wsgi specification](https://pythonhosted.org/pulsar/apps/wsgi/async.html#application-handlers).
The server thinks you are returning an iterator an therefore it treats at such, in the same way as standard wsgi does.

In python 3.5 we can distinguish between coroutines and generators thanks to the new ``async`` keyword. The new syntax will allow for coroutines to be returned (and therefore your example will work), but for now that is not supported.

For now, if you want an async application handler you need to return a future, not a coroutine. In your case you could do:
```python
   @route(rule='/push', method='POST')
    def push(self, request):
        return asyncio.async(self._push(request))

    def _push(self, request):
        body_data = yield from request.body_data
        return request.response
```
The error message is correct. You returned a generator and did not set the headers. Returning the ``request.response`` object as result of the future will be set the headers for you.",{},,User,False
