8053,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-20 17:45:37+00:00,19056610,SecurityInnovation/PGPy,2621594,Commod0re,320350,SecurityInnovation,236753457,309835051,"Wow, very cool pull request - thank you for contributing! I do have a concern I'd like to discuss before merging

As-is, `PGPKey.decrypt` would refuse to even try decrypting a message with a thrown keyid. I'm a little reluctant to do a release where PGPy can produce a message that it can't also consume. So, I'd like to maybe hold off on merging this until after 0.4.2 is released. I am open to being convinced to merge this sooner, though (particularly if someone, myself included, can make time to update `PGPKey.decrypt` to handle thrown keyids properly)",{},,User,False
8064,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-25 23:17:21+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,1039369,nchammas,327752,boto,153138407,275263528,"Same here. It seems there was a burst these past few days of security groups taking a while to propagate.

Generally speaking, I wish boto3 offered a model of interacting with AWS that didn't require us to be mindful of eventual consistency in all these different situations. You make a call that changes state, and it blocks until the change has propagated as necessary. In many (perhaps even most?) situations, I think developers would happily take that tradeoff of slower calls in exchange for consistency. It makes things simpler.

But anyway, I guess that's a discussion for another time.",{},,User,False
