8306,IssueCommentEvent,2016-01-18 17:08:29+00:00,1372698,Pylons/colander,4029388,tisdall,452227,Pylons,75946674,172593450,"@mmerickel - I think this can be closed now than #225 has been merged in.

There's no way to support `drop` in a tuple since the length is fixed and the order is what's used to determine how the value is interpreted.  The best you could do is drop values off the end of the tuple since dropping values in the middle would change how subsequent values were interpreted.",{},,User,False
8308,IssueCommentEvent,2017-07-08 17:22:06+00:00,2999982,Pylons/waitress,649426,bertjwregeer,452227,Pylons,241458070,313869264,"@Sanjay-B You'll want to make sure to configure the root logger in Python (`logging.getLogger()`) and make sure it has a handler on it that outputs to `stdout`:

```
logging_format = '[%(asctime)s] (Testcase) - %(levelname)s - %(name)s - %(message)s'
ch = logging.StreamHandler()
ch.setFormatter(logging.Formatter(logging_format))
rootlog = logging.getLogger()
rootlog.setLevel(logging.WARN)
rootlog.addHandler(ch)
logger = logging.getLogger('waitress')
logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
```

The logger ""waitress"" rolls up into the root logger, and will thus output to the console suing the `StreamHandler` which by default will log to `stderr`.

Python logging unfortunately is a minefield.",{},,User,False
