8761,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-18 19:45:14+00:00,54980593,pypa/setuptools,308610,jaraco,647025,pypa,171361067,240834732,"@byandby In investigating pypa/pip#3917, I was able to replicate your issue:

```
$ cat /Library/Python/2.7/site-packages/easy-install.pth                       
./mercurial_keyring-0.6.7-py2.7.egg
./keyring-5.3-py2.7.egg
./lxml-3.4.4-py2.7-macosx-10.10-intel.egg
./importlib2-3.5.0.2-py2.7.egg
./future-0.14.3-py2.7.egg
./dulwich-0.12.0-py2.7-macosx-10.11-intel.egg
./setuptools-25.2.0-py2.7.egg
$ cat `which easy_install-2.7`
#!/System/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/2.7/Resources/Python.app/Contents/MacOS/Python
# EASY-INSTALL-ENTRY-SCRIPT: 'setuptools==25.2.0','console_scripts','easy_install-2.7'
__requires__ = 'setuptools==25.2.0'
import sys
from pkg_resources import load_entry_point

if __name__ == '__main__':
    sys.exit(
        load_entry_point('setuptools==25.2.0', 'console_scripts', 'easy_install-2.7')()
    )
$ easy_install-2.7
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/usr/local/bin/easy_install-2.7"", line 9, in <module>
    load_entry_point('setuptools==25.2.0', 'console_scripts', 'easy_install-2.7')()
  File ""/System/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/2.7/Extras/lib/python/pkg_resources.py"", line 357, in load_entry_point
    return get_distribution(dist).load_entry_point(group, name)
  File ""/System/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/2.7/Extras/lib/python/pkg_resources.py"", line 2394, in load_entry_point
    return ep.load()
  File ""/System/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/2.7/Extras/lib/python/pkg_resources.py"", line 2108, in load
    entry = __import__(self.module_name, globals(),globals(), ['__name__'])
  File ""build/bdist.macosx-10.11-intel/egg/setuptools/__init__.py"", line 11, in <module>
  File ""build/bdist.macosx-10.11-intel/egg/setuptools/extern/__init__.py"", line 1, in <module>
ImportError: No module named extern
```

What's happening is the `from pkg_resources` is importing pkg_resources from setuptools-1.1.6, but then the call to `load_entry_point('setuptools==25.2.0')` is loading the later installed package and loading the console entry points for it, which is making the later setuptools package available, but since `pkg_resources` is already the old version, it doesn't have the interface that later setuptools relies on.",{},,User,False
