9128,IssueCommentEvent,2015-01-20 22:02:16+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,263366,emmanuelle,897180,scikit-image,26765479,70743235,"@jni thanks for the link, I must confess I didn't know your blog! I have been away from scikit-image development for too long :-).

I can indeed add a dimension to 2D grayscale images. It's just that in the Cython code, when initializing an array with ``cdef DTYPE_t [:, ::1] result = np.zeros_like(padded)`` I understand that it is performance-critical to specify that the array is C-contiguous and that elements along the last dimension are one element apart in memory (which is not very interesting if the last dimension has only one element). But maybe this notation just means that the array is C-contiguous and the performance will be the same on an array of shape (n_x, n_y) and (n_x, n_y, 1). Checking a possible performance change is the easiest way to be sure of that!",{},,User,False
