9777,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-18 07:40:20+00:00,14829536,pydata/numexpr,1852447,jpivarski,1284191,pydata,332983179,397967836,"Thanks! I'll make the language used to fill histograms conform to this list. There's already a large overlap and renaming ""acos"" → ""arccos"" (etc) is easy enough, but there's also a few extra functions that I have, like ""factorial"" (because it's in Python's math library) and ""heaviside"" (because it's in Numpy) and a few extra that you have (""crosspower""? ""fpclassify""?). Most of the ones I was lacking are casting functions.

Here's a complete list of functions that I thought were important but aren't in your list, in case they were oversights:

* ""min"" and ""max"" (rather than ""fmin"" and ""fmax"", applies to integers)
* ""rad2deg"" and ""deg2rad"" (Numpy spellings), as well as ""degrees"" and ""radians"" (Numpy and Python-math, though I think the names with a ""2"" in them are more clear)
* ""factorial"" (Python-math; can be computed from ""lgamma"" applied to integers `x`: `numpy.round(numpy.exp(lgamma(x + 1)))`)
* ""gamma"", which is `exp(lgamma(x))`; I'm not sure what your ""tgamma"" is but I'll look it up
* ""pow""; you have the `**` operator, but particularly complex equations are easier to read with ""pow"" as a function
* ""heaviside""
* ""logaddexp"" and ""logaddexp2""
* ""sign""

One direction where numexpr 3 is going that I won't be able to follow: assignments. I need the functions to be pure expressions because I construct a dependency graph and arrange instructions to avoid recalculating duplicate subexpressions. The use for this is that particle physicists want to fill hundreds of histograms with very similar quantities; manually optimizing them with explicit temporaries conflicts with clarity— they're easier to read as a flat list of expressions. Therefore, I do something similar to numexpr's aggressive mode (but maybe beyond it), reorganizing the expressions to automatically identify temporary quantities*. However, this requires referential transparency: if assignments are allowed, they'd be used as substitutions, and in-place mutations would be completely impossible.

But in the end, that means that I can say I support a _subset_ of numexpr 3's functionality: just the pure expressions.

* I know that this wrongly assumes floating point associativity. My users aren't depending on that level of precision.
",{},NONE,User,False
