<details><summary><i>Previously, adorokhine (Alexander Dorokhine) wrote…</i></summary><blockquote>

The problem here is that all python modules are global, and it's likely psutil would have already been installed by something else. For example, it's a mandatory dependency on ubuntu (cannot be removed) and ships by default with many windows python distributions including activestate (cannot be removed). Ubuntu 10.04 for example ships with psutil 1.2.1.

If we add a version requirement on such a system, setup.py will fail:
`pkg_resources.VersionConflict: (psutil 1.2.1 (/usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages), Requirement.parse('psutil>=5.2.0'))`

But there's no way for the user to fix this because the version that comes on their system cannot be replaced or upgraded in many cases.
</blockquote></details>

Maybe we can require a lower version to lower the impact?
I think a user can still remove existing version of psutil then install the new version.

But if not, let's specify the exact cut off version in the comment line below.

