10556,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-23 20:00:42+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,115146,jberkus,1564818,zalando,306911907,375782219,"@bradnicholson no, it's not, and no, it won't.

The erasure is specifically if you're still at step 7 in the sequence above.  That is, postgres-0 has no data and postgres-1 and postgres-2 haven't connected yet.

If you delete the initialization key at that stage, then postgres-0 will intialize its data directory and claim the master key.  postgres-1 and postgres-2 will then come up, and discover that postgres-0 is the master, and attempt to restart replication from it.  In a best-case scenario, they will simply fail to replicate and wait for administator intervention.  However, between pg_rewind and however you have your health checks set up, what can happen is that postgres-1,2 can be failed out and restarted replicating from postgres-0's empty database.

So I suppose ""... can lead to erasure of all of your data."" would me a more accurate way to put it.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
10559,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-04 06:59:11+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,32459778,Valeriyy,1564818,zalando,262121064,334066523,"> You can have postgresql HA with only two nodes, Patroni will promote replica to the master if master failed

