10573,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-14 09:06:40+00:00,38744670,zalando/patroni,339913,alexeyklyukin,1564818,zalando,257640761,329421195,"Normally, the replica that promotes makes sure it restores all available WAL segments before proceeding with promotion (this is done by PostgreSQL), and the master is also archiving all WAL segments and waiting for the streaming replicas to get up-to-date during its shutdown (also done by PostgreSQL). Therefore, as long as this is a controlled switchover and the former master is available during it there should not be any data loss.

It is rather different in the case of the failover, when the former master goes away unexpectedly. There, you cannot guarantee that all data is shipped to the replicas before the promotion, however, Patroni prevents any replica to promote that is more than  `maximum_lag_on_failover` bytes behind the last reported master position.",{},MEMBER,User,False
