10959,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-01 09:04:11+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,554159,xunzhang,2374376,clab,269802704,341042009,"Hi @mattr1, thanks for the discussion here.

The reason why I added this is to support partial model or parameter load. Besides, a model file may include lots of `ParameterCollection`s and independent parameters(for example a checkpoint or anything users want to save together). So it should be necessary to skip the unwanted stuff and find the required data location quickly.

To address the two issues you mentioned. For the first one, it's not difficult to handle both the case of LF and CR-LF (in particular we need to skip CR stuff). For the second one, I think it's on purpose to make a readable text format. We fixed the length of every float number to `[+-]X.YYYe[+-]ZZZ`, where the length of 8, the length of ZZZ is 2. Users can modify the value using this format, it will not break the `byte_count`. I think the scientific representation is kind of letting users be aware of it's designed format, so when they want to modify the value to do the experiment, they will follow this. Does it make sense?

`TextSaver`/`TextLoader` is readable and can be easily modified saver-loader. We have a general saver and loader class which will be extended to other saver-loader such as the binary saver/loader. I think @pmichel31415 is working on this part (https://github.com/clab/dynet/issues/648). A binary saver-loader will surely have more efficient CPU time and less space usage.

",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
