11070,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-03 22:46:15+00:00,24213271,adobe-type-tools/afdko,2856984,readroberts,2768660,adobe-type-tools,337316194,402313200,"It is correct that makeotfexe writes a negative advance width value as a signed short (well, it writes it as an unsigned short, but does so after simply casting the the width value to an unsigned short, so you get the same two bytes as if you had written a signed short).  65536 - x is what you get if you read a negative signed short value as an unsigned short.  I am a little concerned about making this illegal, as developers have used negative widths in some cases - I vaguely remember a discussion about Semitic fonts using negative widths; it was certainly used to get around bugs in GPOS in the early days of OpenType. If the consensus is that it is time to disallow negative values, would you 
 prefer to have negative advance widths set to 0, with a warning, or a fatal error?",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
