11332,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-03 23:36:26+00:00,37775115,uqfoundation/multiprocess,321534,mmckerns,2855931,uqfoundation,211774014,284100493,"So, on windows, you need a compiler.  I have several places where if `_multiprocess` doesn't import, then it falls back to `_multiprocessing`, so it can work without the compiler but it still uses `pickle` instead of `dill`.  I'm only catching `ImportError` and not `SystemError`, so I expect that in 2.7 it's throwing a `ImportError`.

I'll check on windows with 3.5 and see if I can reproduce your error.

There are free MS Windows C++ compilers available that are compatible with python 3.5, I'd suggest you go get one from MS if you don't have a compiler.

Alternately, you can wait an undisclosed amount of time... I just started building wheels, and I will release wheels for `multiprocess` soon (so you won't need a compiler). I'd suggest getting the compiler as it's a much more immediate solution.

If you try to send a `lambda` through a `map` and it fails, then I believe that will also confirm it's a compiler issue, since it would rely on `pickle`

",{},,User,False
