12327,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-29 20:47:08+00:00,55245781,sassoftware/saspy,38366806,JTH-03-027,5289877,sassoftware,327429370,392938570,"Thanks.  I did some testing and, yes, we have the ability to use the saspy disconnect() method, then disconnect from a network, and then re-connect to the identical SAS GRID session after re-connecting to the network. That is quite handy.

After I opened my new issue, I found this old issue:
https://github.com/sassoftware/saspy/issues/131

and saw the _endsas() method.  I tried it.  I got the message that the SAS Session had been terminated, but, the task was still running on the Linux SAS GRID.

However, the good news is that after I terminated the Python kernel, and shut down the ipynb, this time, the SAS GRID Task *did* shut down.  It took several minutes, but, it did shut down as expected.

So, in summary:


  1.  We can use the disconnect() saspy method to disconnect from a running SAS session, disconnect from a WAN, connect to a wifi router, and then successfully resume executing saspy methods in the ipynb.  Very nice.
  2.  We tried using the _endsas() method.  We received an indication in the ipynb that the session had been ended, but, that task showed up as still running on our Linux SAS GRID.
  3.  Terminating the Python kernel and closing the ipynb DID cause the Linux SAS GRID task to shut down correctly (after a delay of a couple minutes).

It is still unexplained why the Linux SAS Grid did not shut down when we terminated the kernel and ended the ipynb last Friday?

Thanks for the fast response to our question.

John

From: Tom Weber [mailto:notifications@github.com]
Sent: Tuesday, May 29, 2018 4:32 PM
To: sassoftware/saspy <saspy@noreply.github.com>
Cc: Hixon, John <jhixon@amgen.com>; Author <author@noreply.github.com>
Subject: [external] Re: [sassoftware/saspy] Ability to terminate a SAS session from within an ipynb? (#137)


Hey thanks!, yes, you can terminate the SASsession ('sas' in the case below) with the _endsas() method:

sas._endsas()

I am concerned about you not seeing your grid session terminate though.
Two thoughts on that.

  1.  just closing the notebook doesn't stop the python process (which is also the saspy process). But stopping the process via 'restart notebook' or file->close&halt should shut down the python process and saspy should end the SAS session (does _endsas() internally).
  2.  There is a fix at master for a case where if you have the ability to 'reconnect' then when I shut down the SAS session, it didn't go away be cause it was waiting for a possible reconnect. I think that bug is only fixed at master, not out in the latest pypi package. It's possible you are seeing this if you don't have that fix. If you use the _endsas() method and the Grid workspace server doesn't go away, I suspect this is the issue. You can tell if you have the reconnect capability set up by just trying the disconnect method; what it prints out will either be it worked, or you can't use it cuz it's not configured.

sas.disconnect()



# you should see one or the other otf these messages

'Succesfully disconnected. Be sure to have a valid network connection before submitting anything else.'

or

'This workspace server is not configured for reconnecting. Did not disconnect.'

Thanks!
Tom

