13114,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-09 00:46:48+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1640669,damianavila,6392739,conda,165942681,238421478,"> Thanks @bollwyvl for the reply, I've updated and now I got ""Python [default]"" as the kernel name, instead of the Python 3 that used to be.

That's expected, that `python [default]` use Jupyter's default kernel name ('python2' or 'python3') for the current env... so you are safe to use that one.
Every `Python 3` notebook will be opened as a `python [default]` one and if you share a notebook with this kernel in it with someone without `nb_conda_kernels` they will be able to open it and they will see the `Python 3` name.",{},,User,False
