13910,IssueCommentEvent,2015-04-06 16:54:27+00:00,23984796,jupyter/nbgrader,83444,jhamrick,7388996,jupyter,66480345,90154107,"> In what situations have you run into a need for this?

There's two cases where this might be necessary:

1. You provide students with a supplementary file, but then realize there's a bug in it. You post a clarification to your class saying they should make a change to the file and that they need to pass the tests with this change, for example. However, not all students may make the change, so you want to overwrite the file for everyone during grading to make sure that everyone is actually running the same code.

2. Relatedly, it's possible students could change the code or data that is given to them so that they pass the tests without actually completing the assignment. I've also had students who changed the code they were given to add print statements -- which is fine, except that then during grading you can end up with a cell output that is hundreds or thousands of lines long, so it's nice to be able to revert back to the version of the code that they were given when the assignment was released.

> How does an instructor say which files are to be overcopied or not?

Good question. At the moment, it will overwrite all of the files that have a version in the source directory (with the exception of `.ipynb` files), but perhaps there should be a configurable option to either whitelist or blacklist files for overwriting. My preference would be a blacklist -- by default, overwrite everything, but allow some things to be excluded if you actually are expecting students to change them. What do you think?",{},,User,False
