13994,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-20 17:16:01+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,327925,takluyver,7388996,jupyter,283555574,353125434,"From Jupyter's point of view, nothing is being executed when you load. The Javascript/HTML code is the output of the cell, and that's saved in the notebook file. When you load it, the output is 'displayed' on the page without going through the kernel. And displaying Javascript causes the browser to run it.

Apart from the trust check, Jupyter doesn't do anything special with Javascript. It's just an output format that makes things happen when it's displayed. And all a `%%javascript` cell does is send its input back as output with the metadata to say it's Javascript.",{},OWNER,User,False
