14133,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-12 10:20:41+00:00,1199632,schematics/schematics,120501,charlax,7866441,schematics,132987826,183262478,"The problem with the random behavior is that an exception will be raised when comparing a naive datetime with an aware one. Yet if on production I always expect the datetime to be timezone-aware, I see no reason why mock object created by schematics include naive timezone. This will force people to either change the `_mock` to always return timezone-aware datetime, or change their code to accommodate the tests (which is a big no-no).

So to recap the options:

1. Always return aware and naive datetime at random.
2. Observe `tzd` parameter to return the correct mocked value.

Logic for option 2.:

* `tzd == 'reject'`: always return naive datetime.
* `tzd == 'allow'`: return naive/aware datetime at random.
* `tzd == 'require'`: return timezone-aware datetime in random timezone.
* `tzd == 'utc'`: return timezone-aware datetime in UTC.

This seems to be pretty intuitive.

cc @mjrk and @j2labs.",{},,User,False
