14598,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-20 21:38:05+00:00,41756998,pytest-dev/pytest-xdist,1085180,nicoddemus,8897583,pytest-dev,202246262,274186632,"Hi @edbrannin,

It is OK to post questions here, don't worry!

The short answer to your question is that no, it is not possible to use locks and semaphores in the current implementation of `pytest-xdist`. `pytest-xdist` uses `execnet` as a backend, and AFAIK it doesn't have any synchronization mechanisms.

But if all you want is some kind of lock, you can try to implement something for your test suite based on a [file lock](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/filelock/). I've done it in the past and it works well.

As for using `multiprocessing` as a backend in pytest-xdist, that's not possible in the current design. However, I feel it would be possible to write a new plugin using the current pytest-xdist codebase as starting point which used `multiprocessing` as backend, specially if you just want to use multiple cores in the same computer and drop some features like multi-python version testing support, remote testing, rsync, etc. If you keep the same architecture and use the same general design (master spawns workers, workers collect items, master coordinates test execution in workers), you should be fine. 

Take a look at our [OVERVIEW](https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest-xdist/blob/master/OVERVIEW.md) for a more detailed description.
",{},,User,False
