15245,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-06 06:45:35+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,304265,frol,10334301,marshmallow-code,211954927,284315516,"Without this change we have inconsistent behavior as `ordered` is inferred from base classes in `__new__`, so I believe that either you drop that logic (that would be sad) or complete it with this change.",{},,User,False
15251,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-25 21:11:00+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,365247,nackjicholson,10334301,marshmallow-code,344604045,407897090,"Here, I used one of the only libraries in python that I could find that actually handles iso8601 datetime strings correctly and according to the actual ISO 8601 standard. 

https://pypi.org/project/isodate/

```python
import isodate as iso
from marshmallow import fields, Schema


class ISOTzAwareDatetimeField(fields.Field):
    def _serialize(self, value, attr, obj):
        return iso.datetime_isoformat(value)

    def _deserialize(self, value, attr, data):
        return iso.parse_datetime(value)


import unittest
from datetime import datetime


class MySchema(Schema):
    foo = ISOTzAwareDatetimeField(required=True)


class TestISOTzAwareDatetimeField(unittest.TestCase):
    """"""
    python -m unittest -v test.test_fields.TestISOTzAwareDatetimeField
    """"""
    def test_serialize(self):
        schema = MySchema()
        actual = schema.dump({'foo': datetime(2018, 7, 25, tzinfo=iso.UTC)})
        expected = {'foo': '2018-07-25T00:00:00Z'}
        self.assertEqual(actual, expected)

    def test_deserialize(self):
        schema = MySchema()
        actual = schema.load({'foo': '2018-07-25T00:00:00Z'})
        expected = {'foo': datetime(2018, 7, 25, tzinfo=iso.UTC)}
        self.assertEqual(actual, expected)

```",{},NONE,User,False
