15290,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-30 01:12:21+00:00,40094312,pyserial/pyserial,21270768,neilwhelchel,10537924,pyserial,171903563,243304648,"@altendky (Please keep in mind I am not a PySerial developer, I am a fly on the wall, so I might not be speaking for the intentions of the developers or the project.) Yes, it is quite easy to follow the symlink to determine this. My point is that PySerial should not do this. It is my opinion that the application that is using PySerial should follow the symlinks and work out the device that it is going to use. Just as it is the job of the application that is using PySerial to set the comm parameters, it is also the job of that application to know if the parameters apply to a certain device. The line has to be somewhere, maybe there needs to be an add-on to PySerial that works out these things and contains a database of device capabilities. (This is a big project to keep up to date as there are new devices popping up every day or so.) The big problem here is that the actual Linux serial device API (termios) is BADLY broken, and it literally does not tell you when the hardware is not capable of accepting what settings you want. In most cases, setting unsupported parameters silently fails and leaves the user with patches of missing hair.",{},,User,False
