15659,IssueCommentEvent,2015-11-10 19:47:25+00:00,41312700,symengine/symengine.py,4260188,woodscn,11509221,symengine,116178081,155545960,"The whole process ends up being a bit hackish; it's entirely possible that I'm messing something up on my end. I'm also working with an Anaconda installation, in my user directory, and I'm running python 3.4 rather than 2.7. Lots of possibilities there.

Here's my process, FWIW, running cmake version 3.3.2 and python 3.4.

git clone both symengine and symengine.py
git checkout specific commit in symegine
cmake -D<set install path to be ~, which has bin, lib, and include directories available> .
This throws errors, but running cmake again finishes cleanly. No idea why.
make install
cd to symengine.py 
python setup.py install build --symengine-dir=<~>
Again, cmake throws errors the first time, but the second time finishes. 
Testing results in the error: 
```~$ python -c ""import symengine""
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<string>"", line 1, in <module>
