15696,IssueCommentEvent,2017-08-15 10:10:29+00:00,32944298,Z3Prover/z3,511795,delcypher,11668813,Z3Prover,250167179,322430607,"> Sorry, but this is completely unnecessary. What is the motivation for this and why would we make this change at this point in time? This can easily wait until January, when we switch to VS2013.

I don't use Windows much so this doesn't really affect me too much but why would you need to support a 5 year old compiler, when much newer versions are easily available and usable? Perhaps you have projects that **only** build against the older MSVC and also depend on Z3? If so that might be a legitimate reason to maintain MSVC 2012 support. However at some point those projects will have to upgrade or face (eventually) becoming irrelevant.

Without context it is difficult for me to say whether I think the change is ""completely unnecessary"". I personally think it's a good thing to drop a compiler like MSVC 2012 so that the ability to use more C++11 features is available.

Just my 2c.",{},,User,False
