15757,IssueCommentEvent,2015-05-08 14:27:15+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,629706,f0k,11752110,Lasagne,57096687,100246892,"> I still think the primary/advertised way should be one or the other.

I'd advertise `nonlinearity=...` as the primary way and note that the other one is possible as well, and allows for parameterized, learnable nonlinearities. Keras does it quite similarly in their README.

> The proposed new way is much cleaner, imo, and less confusing to new users.

Which ""new way"" do you refer to here? Having nonlinearities as separate layers?

> Is anyone working on this?

We already added a layer that does nothing but apply a nonlinearity, that was in #225.
We more or less agreed on changing the default nonlinearity to `identity` in a dev meeting, but there are still objections within the core team and nobody started working on it. I guess the more arguments or proponents we have for changing it, the more likely it will happen. (Full disclosure: I'm one of the proponents.) Discussion on that should take place in #138.",{},,User,False
15761,IssueCommentEvent,2015-05-20 14:56:45+00:00,23924195,Lasagne/Lasagne,43829,benanne,11752110,Lasagne,77646414,103917928,"I don't know. I guess let's try to merge it with `norm_constraint`, there is a lot of overlap. Then we'll see if it's too complicated or not.

Maybe `norm_constraint` and `step_scaling` could be more specialized functions that both use the same underlying function? Something like that? I don't know :) `step_scaling` seems to me like it might not be the best name for this either, since it refers to a specific use case of this operation and not really the operation itself.",{},,User,False
