16149,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-05 10:43:11+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,6248219,deb0ch,12973369,dronekit,224760959,349265987,"Just to give some context to my comments, I'm using the set_attitude_target message in a production project. I use it to control my drone's position based on the output of a lidar, and based my code off of this example.

So I went through it IRL and all the comments that I made are based on caveats that I encountered, and I have real life testing feedback if you guys need.",{},NONE,User,False
16150,IssueCommentEvent,2016-01-11 17:46:50+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,2956460,squilter,12973369,dronekit,125102970,170630990,"Okay I found it.  The problem is in ArduCopter.  I'll talk to Randy and try to fix it, but the problem already exists in 3.3, so we need to figure out how to proceed here.

After sending a `MAV_CMD_REQUEST_AUTOPILOT_CAPABILITIES`, ArduCopter responds with a `AUTOPILOT_VERSION` packet, which includes a version number (e.g. 3.4.0-dev), and a bitmask of supported capabilities.  The problem is that if this packet is requested in the first few seconds after the vehicle boots, it will send back a packet with `0`'s in the capability bitmask (version field is fine).  

So it worked fine for me because I started SITL, then started dronekit.  If it happens the other way around, the packet that is received in response will have an empty `capabilities` field, causing the test to fail.",{},,User,False
