16301,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-26 13:10:57+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,1102021,rob-c,13271048,ganga-devs,172427205,249565018,Can someone please review this again please.,{},,User,False
16302,IssueCommentEvent,2016-01-15 12:45:55+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,1102021,rob-c,13271048,ganga-devs,122052879,171951499,"I've looked into the ElementTree in the past but this will likely require a completely new implementation of VStreamer from the ground up, although I think it supports parallel parsing of elements which could be nice.

The average DiracFile is only about ~10 lines of XML but with LHCbDataset from a book-keeping query most of that data is set to empty so we have an LFN stored about about 10 lines of empty string objects (and the empty subfiles).

The problem is that this obviously doesn't scale very well as bzipping one of these drops to ~55kb very quickly so this is highly compressible data. Granted maybe we could drop a lot of the whitespace in this file but the file is still too large to process in it's current form and constructing 8k DiracFile objects is a non trivial task as it takes a few seconds (I'm tempted to look into copying the objects from one already in memory in future rather than constructing a new object each time as this can potentially be a lot cheaper)",{},,User,False
16304,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-23 09:58:23+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,61316,milliams,13271048,ganga-devs,135538664,187630961,"The problem that nose was having is that since doctest imports every module individually it was getting into very strange situations where, for example, there was a class in a file in a directory of the same name (e.g. `class MTRunner` in `.../MTRunner/MTRunner.py`) it would try to import `MTRunner` and then do somethin with it and it would say something like `AttributeError: module 'MTRunner' has no attribute 'start'`. This is a known bug with nosetests which is never going to be fixed.

The main reason for me avoiding `doctest.DocTestSuite` is that it's too manual. The point of using nose or pytest is that it can automatically find all the tests in our codebase and having to add boilerplate to run doctests (which are supposed to be almost boilerplate-free) seems a bit heavy. Given that pytest finds them without problems (and is maintained and will have bugs fixed) swung the favour their way.

I did look at [nose2](https://github.com/nose-devs/nose2) which would otherwise have been good but it was suffering the same import bug as nose.",{},,User,False
