16569,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-24 13:09:14+00:00,46374199,IntelRealSense/librealsense,41145062,MartyG-RealSense,14095512,IntelRealSense,343993392,407400336,"Apologies that this process is taking a while.   It feels like we are making progress through a process of elimination though!

My sense is that D415 probably is an appropriate camera for this application, since new tablets from Panasonic and MobileDemand use the D410 and D415 cameras respectively for their scanning.  So it should work.  The problem is in minimizing bad data from proximity to the object.",{},NONE,User,False
16571,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-08 16:49:27+00:00,46374199,IntelRealSense/librealsense,134740,agrunnet,14095512,IntelRealSense,303321462,371547969,"@danielw256 the RealSense D4xx series experience no optical interference, which makes them really good for multicamera usages.  Even though the multiple cameras overlap their field-of-view, there is no information contained in the projected patterns- they only serve to provide texture for stereo matching. So the more texture, the merrier. 
What you are referring to is how people have tried to hack structured light solutions to work, which do interfere with each other since it is imperative that each system knows which projection dots belong to their camera. This has been done by 1. trying to time multiplex, and 2. By shaking one camera. The idea is to make the pattern of the OTHER camera blur out so they just provide a uniform background. This is really impractical as you can imagine. 
Furthermore, Intel is working on releasing official support multicamera HW sync, so each frame is capture at exactly the same time. For many applications this is actually not a requirement and it is fine to just use the time-stamps to align frames. However, for those who want sub-ms sync, that should become available in the not-so-distant future.    ",{},NONE,User,False
16572,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-11 13:00:31+00:00,46374199,IntelRealSense/librealsense,22654243,zivsha,14095512,IntelRealSense,295223187,364750000,"Hi @summer1216 ,
Hope you managed to work this out by now, if not then I hope the following will help you do that.
The texture coordinates syntax is typically a pair of floats `(u,v)` where `u`,`v` are between `[0-1]`. 
The semantics of it is the location in the 2D texture image (RGB frame in our case) of where to take the color of a 3D point.
If you look at how we set the texture mapping values, you can see how to get the color pixel from these values:
https://github.com/IntelRealSense/librealsense/blob/9437bc24c0f4ce16193f1045ceea703a8151b96d/src/proc/pointcloud.cpp#L178

https://github.com/IntelRealSense/librealsense/blob/9437bc24c0f4ce16193f1045ceea703a8151b96d/src/proc/pointcloud.cpp#L37

As you can see we take the pixel's (x,y) and devise it by the width and height of the image to get a normalized value between [0,1] (well actually, this could be <0 or >1 since the projection might suffer from distortions - such values should be discarded when you revert the process).
So after calculating the pointcloud and mapping the texture, if you call `points.get_texture_coordinates()` per index you will get the `(u,v)` and by multiplying it with the color image's resolution (and clamping) you can get the `(x,y)` pixel from the image where you can query it for its RGB values. 
",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
