2. No, the actions predicted by two DDPG policies stay same until 1 or 2 epochs (800 episodes of 50 time-steps each), and then they slowly differ (and hence, future observations differ too and it snowballs)
3. I haven't tested this out yet",{},NONE,User,False
16705,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-30 16:41:22+00:00,92238803,openai/baselines,7438704,alcinos,14957082,openai,239559073,312316178,"I think they did that to match what DeepMind did in their original paper. Back then, they considered that an episode is over once you loose your first life (whether that makes sense or not is I think questionnable, but one intuition is that it gives stronger signal to the agent that isn't otherwise punished for death in most games).

So their wrapper basically detects when you loose your first life and set done = True. However as you can see, it is still possible to continue playing since the underlying game is not finished yet. 

To solve you problem, you can simply remove the ``EpisodicLifeEnv`` from the wrapper ( baselines/baselines/common/atari_wrappers_deprecated.py:212)",{},,User,False
