17390,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-23 07:36:44+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1322974,anntzer,17565521,pybind,172510144,241651475,"To be honest I don't really understand the criticism.

On the issue of the dependency on pybind11:

Either one wants to write a `setup.py` that will work even if pybind11 is not installed yet (in which case you need to go through the contorsions mentioned by @SylvainCorlay) or one accepts that similarly to numpy and cython, a dependency on pybind11 can only be *documented*, not programmatically written in the `setup.py`.  I have chosen to follow the second option, and thus don't need to do anything fancy to delay the call to `get_include`.  Of course, nothing prevents you from sticking to @SylvainCorlay's `setup.py`.

On the issue of ""hiding logic"":

AFAICT any extension module that relies on pybind11 (and setuptools) needs to pass some options to the Extension class: `language` must be set to `""c++""`, `include_dirs` needs to include the pybind11 include directories, and a c++11 or c++14 compatibility flag to the C compiler.  Additionally, it is recommanded to set the default visibility of symbols to hidden.  These are the *only* things this PR does (modulo a few platform-specific things (`/EHsc` on Windows, etc.) I copy-pasted from @SylvainCorlay's example, but I don't really know anything about compilation options on Mac or Windows, so if they are irrelevant I can strip them out too); in other words, I expect any project that relies on setuptools and pybind11 to have to need some similar code (but please let me know if I am wrong).

Note that *no additional hooks* are provided: the Extension class still provides the same interface as the normal `setuptools.Extension`, and it is trivially possible to override the defaults provided by `pybind11.setuptools.Extension` by adding more include dirs (which go in front of the defaults), more compilation flags (which go after the defaults), or simply using sticking to `setuptools.Extension` instead of `pybind11.setuptools.Extension`.",{},,User,False
17392,IssueCommentEvent,2016-12-18 14:01:47+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,4967343,patrikhuber,17565521,pybind,196250028,267822830,"@aldanor: Aaaah. I think I'm getting there - the hard way. I didn't figure out the ""easy"" way so I dug deeper and deeper, unnecessarily. And I got stuck a bit on `py::array_t<T>` as well and didn't use `py::array`. With all this knowledge it turns out the solution is really easy ;-)

There's one last issue, and that one smells a bit like a possible bug: I can test for any type and it works perfectly, but not for `int32` and `uint32`. 

```
auto buf = pybind11::array::ensure(src);
if (!buf) return false;
std::cout << buf.dtype() << std::endl;
if (buf.dtype() == pybind11::dtype::of<std::int32_t>()) {
    // do something...
} else if (...) {
    // another type...
} // ...
```
This works for any type I tried (float, std::uint8_t, etc.) but it just jumps over the `if` for int32/uint32 types. Using just `int` or `unsigned int` also does not work.
For example, calling this function with:
`test(np.array([1, 2, 3], dtype=numpy.int32))`
prints `int32` to the console, which means the dtype is actually int32, but then the comparison in the `if` is false for any integer type that I tried.

This is under VS2015U3, x64, and python-3.5.2 64bit.",{},,User,False
