17520,IssueCommentEvent,2017-08-16 15:13:31+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,295816,erikrose,17889013,certbot,249266124,322804539,"@pombredanne We did consider a lot of alternatives, including bundling. certbot, like your tool, has to run on a variety of platforms and architectures. Since not all of our dependencies are pure Python, we'd either have to release a multiplicity of bundles (which is the tack I see you took) or else one very large one which contains all possible builds of, say, [cryptography](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/cryptography/), each of which is 1-2MB. I see you went ahead and built bundles for each platform and count on users to know which to download. This actually seems like more work and more opportunity for error than just delegating that problem to pip and PyPI. (It also doesn't hurt that PyPI has its own CDN and so handles the distribution of the great majority of our bits for us.) In any case, we'd still need a self-updating certbot-auto-like script to install the requisite OS packages—we'd never be rid of that layer. But I'm all ears for an approach that truly simplifies things! Maybe I'm missing something.

Quasi disclaimer: I'm the author of pip's hash-checking features, but I intended them for precisely such cases. Cheers!",{},,User,False
