18536,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-21 15:18:17+00:00,1380748,ninia/jep,5747885,ndjensen,28115331,ninia,334529906,399140948,"That error message:

> 
> Exception in thread ""main"" jep.JepException: <type 'exceptions.ImportError'>: 
> Importing the multiarray numpy extension module failed.  Most
> likely you are trying to import a failed build of numpy.
> If you're working with a numpy git repo, try `git clean -xdf` (removes all
> files not under version control).  Otherwise reinstall numpy.

is coming out of numpy.  Do you have more than one Python install on your system and therefore potentially more than one numpy?  It's possible that when you are running Jep from the command line it's using one set of Python (and numpy) libraries while running Jep from your Java application is using a different Python and its numpy libraries.  Open up the jep script in a text editor and see if you can spot what it is doing differently (especially regarding environment variables) than your Java application.",{},MEMBER,User,False
18544,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-03 00:33:15+00:00,71948498,localstack/localstack,2807888,whummer,28732122,localstack,262156697,333704208,"Thanks for reporting @g-one . Looks like your Python environment is not configured correctly, the `$PATH` environment variable should contain a path to the Python `bin` folder. Which operating system are you on? I'm assuming Mac Os (or Linux) in the instructions below.

You can print the `PATH` using:
```
echo $PATH
```
It should normally contain a path similar to `/Users/__your_username__/Library/Python/2.7/bin`. You can extend your `~/.profile` file and add a new line to it. Note that the actual path may vary depending on your local Python installation.
```
export PATH=/Users/__your_username__/Library/Python/2.7/bin:$PATH
```
Then open a new terminal window, and the path should be set correctly.",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
