18633,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-26 12:30:46+00:00,102692863,onnx/onnx,180987,nouiz,31675368,onnx,268613055,339650171,"I totally agree that keeping the API NumPy compatible is very important!

Le mer. 25 oct. 2017 22:53, Tianqi Chen <notifications@github.com> a écrit :

> This is related to #83 <https://github.com/onnx/onnx/issues/83> But I
> want to raise this as a general issue. Some of the current onnx operators
> are not compatible with numpy.
>
>    - min/max are elementwise instead of reduction. In numpy being maximum
>    and minimum
>    - The broadcast semantics are not ready
>    - split's output attribute naming.
>
> While some of these can be viewed as minor issues. But in general, we can
> find that the frameworks are leaning toward numpy API. So when we design
> our in-memory IR in NNVM, we are starting to adopt the principle that: use
> numpy API when such operator exist
>
> I understand there are concerns about support level and granularity. While
> these are valid concerns, many of them can actually be addressed by other
> operators that are not in numpy(e.g. gemm). I am opening this issue to see
> how other's opinion toward this.
>
> I find the general IR starts into three needs
>
>    - coverage
>    - conciseness
>    - conventional (reflects conventional usage of API)
>
> While it is easy to design for the first two points. Adopting numpy API
> when possible hit the third one more easily.
>
> —
> You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.
